SIMPLE: poorly
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Poorly
<hw>Poor"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>In a poor manner or
condition; without plenty, or sufficiency, or suitable provision for
comfort; <as>as, to live <ex>poorly</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>With little or no success; indifferently; with
little profit or advantage; <as>as, to do <ex>poorly</ex> in
business</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Meanly; without spirit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor is their courage or their wealth so low,⟦br⟧
That from his wars they <qex>poorly</qex> would retire.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Without skill or merit; <as>as, he performs
<ex>poorly</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Poorly off</b></col>, <cd>not well off; not
rich.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poorly</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Poorly
<hw>Poor"ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Somewhat ill; indisposed; not in
health.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Having been <xex>poorly</xex> in health.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>T. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poorness</ent>⟦br⟧
